
ML experiment - Logistic regression.

From a set of features describing a flower, learn and classify
between flowers of 4 types. A first attempt at logistic regression



**Coding dependencies**

Matplotlib.pyplot, Numpy library. 

**Data set** 

There are 4 distinct features. When analyzing the dataset, it is clear that these are linearly independent and viable features. Also no outliers were found.  Further analyzing the distribution gave the below statistics 

Measures of Dispersion  
Minimum \= 1.3  
Maximum \= 5.7  
Range \= 4.4  
Variance \= 2.631875  
Standard Deviation \= 1.6223054582907621

Thus it was decided to continue using all the features by regularizing the values. Data was randomized before the training was done. 

**Splitting the dataset** 

Dataset was split in 70%, 20%, 10% ratio as train, validate and test sets. Validate and test tests were run separately. 

**Model used** 

The model used for this assignment is the regularized logistic regression model with the negative log-likelihood loss function. The cost function associated is 

![][image1]

**Classification and Optimisation** 

For classification, instead of multiclass regression models, the implementation attempted here is **one versus rest classification**. 

Therefore 3 models were created and can be used in combination to decide the classification. Some of the learning parameters used are

|  |  |  |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Decision boundary | Numerical value used over the sigmoid for classification  | 5e-1 |
| Alpha | learning rate  | 1e-1 |
| Lambda | regularization rate   | 7e-1  |
| Iterations per epoch | Number of attempts per iteration  | 1e3   |
| Total epochs  | Total number of iterations  | 1e4 |

**Validations and loss calculation**

Validations were done against each weightset to measure the success rate of the model.
